            81.0,
            985.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "Therefore, for images in the training set, we expect the network to provide an unbiased noise prediction. Since the noise prediction is typically inaccessible in practical applications, we use the reconstructed sample  $ \\hat{x} $ as a proxy. By leveraging the unbiasedness of noise prediction, we show that averaging over multiple independent reconstructed samples  $ \\hat{x}_i $ can significantly reduce estimation error (see Theorem 4.2). However, for images not in the training set, the neural network may not provide an unbiased prediction at these points. The intuition is illustrated in Figure 2.",
        "block_bbox": [
          80,
          995,
          595,
          1254
        ],
        "block_id": 8,
        "block_order": 6,
        "group_id": 8,
        "global_block_id": 59,
        "global_group_id": 59,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
